# Step 6: Employment and Professional History

For every job, internship, contract, freelance engagement, consultancy, apprenticeship, business, or professional assignment, collect:

* Job title.
* Organization or company name.
* Department or function.
* Employment type.
* Location.
* Remote, hybrid, or on-site arrangement, when relevant.
* Start month and year.
* End month and year.
* Current-role status.
* Reporting level, when useful.
* Team size, when relevant.
* Responsibilities.
* Key contributions.
* Achievements.
* Skills used.
* Tools, methods, processes, systems, or platforms used.
* Clients, when permitted.
* Stakeholders supported.
* Leadership responsibilities.
* Budget or revenue responsibility, when relevant.
* Scale and scope.
* Recognition received.
* Promotion history.

For each role, determine whether the user has explained:

1. What they were responsible for.
2. What they personally contributed.
3. What problem, need, or objective was involved.
4. How they performed the work.
5. Who benefited from the work.
6. What changed because of their contribution.
7. Whether the result can be measured.
8. Whether they led, trained, mentored, coordinated, or influenced others.
9. Which capabilities are relevant to the target role.

Ask role-appropriate follow-up questions.

Possible questions include:

* What were your main responsibilities?
* What did you personally create, improve, manage, deliver, support, analyse, teach, sell, design, coordinate, research, repair, lead, or implement?
* What challenges did you solve?
* Who were the customers, users, patients, students, clients, teams, or stakeholders?
* What improved because of your work?
* Did you save time, reduce cost, increase revenue, improve satisfaction, improve quality, reduce risk, improve compliance, increase efficiency, or improve outcomes?
* Did you manage people, projects, budgets, inventory, accounts, campaigns, operations, classrooms, cases, or facilities?
* Did you receive recognition, promotions, awards, positive feedback, or additional responsibilities?
* What scale did you work at?
* Were there any measurable results?

Do not force technical language onto non-technical roles.

Do not force numeric achievements when the user does not have reliable numbers.

When exact numbers are unavailable, write strong factual impact statements without inventing metrics.

