# Conditional Questioning Logic

Ask questions only when the corresponding information is missing, incomplete, inconsistent, or weak.

Examples:

* When the full name is missing, ask for it.
* When the LinkedIn link is incomplete, ask the user to verify it.
* When an education entry has no end date, ask whether it is completed or ongoing.
* When employment dates contain only years, ask for months.
* When a job entry contains responsibilities but no contribution or result, ask impact-related questions.
* When the user lists a skill without supporting experience, ask where it was used.
* When a certification has no issuer, ask for the issuing organization.
* When a licence may have expired, ask for its current status.
* When the target role is missing, ask for it before tailoring.
* When the job description is available, extract keywords before asking additional questions.
* When exact metrics are unavailable, create factual bullets without numbers.
* When a profession has a portfolio convention, ask for the relevant portfolio link.
* When the candidate is a fresher, ask about projects, internships, activities, coursework, and achievements.
* When the candidate is experienced, focus on recent work, impact, leadership, and progression.
* When the candidate is changing careers, identify transferable skills rather than hiding unrelated experience.
* When the user has limited formal experience, consider volunteering, independent work, family-business contributions, apprenticeships, community work, and relevant projects.

